section.section:
Of the 31 members:
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Chapter of the American College of Emergency Physicians;
One shall be a representative of MedChi, The Maryland State Medical Society;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Hospital Association;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland State Council of the Emergency Nurses Association;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Fire and Rescue Institute;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland State Firemen's Association;
One shall be a representative of the Aviation Division of the Department of State Police;
One shall be a representative of the Office of Traffic and Safety of the Maryland Department of Transportation;
One shall be a representative from each of the five regional emergency medical services advisory councils;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Trauma Center Network;
One shall be a representative of a Maryland commercial ambulance service;
One shall be a representative of the Board of Physicians;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Chapter, American College of Surgeons;
One shall be a regional medical director;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Chapter (Chesapeake Bay), American Association of Critical Care Nurses;
One shall be a representative of the Professional Fire Fighters of Maryland;
One shall be a representative of the volunteer field providers;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Metropolitan Fire Chiefs;
One shall be a representative of the Emergency Number Systems Board;
One shall be the Director of the R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center;
One shall be the Director of the National Study Center;
Three shall be members of the general public, one of whom shall reside in a county with a population of less than 175,000;
One shall be a representative of the Committee on Pediatric Emergency Medicine of the American Academy of Pediatrics, Maryland Chapter;
One shall be a representative of the Maryland Society of Anesthesiologists; and
One shall be a helicopter pilot.

text.section:
The Advisory Council shall:
Serve as a principal advisory body to the EMS Board on matters concerning finances, policies, guidelines, regulations, and procedures necessary for the efficient and effective operation of the statewide Emergency Medical Services System and the Institute;
Provide a means by which regional emergency medical services interests can be represented at a statewide level;
Assist in the development of goals for and facilitate the implementation of a comprehensive emergency medical services plan;
Provide assistance in the resolution of interregional and interstate emergency medical services system problems and concerns; and
Perform any other duties as may be requested by the EMS Board or the Governor.
